 {"id":"wa-1j0ye","title":"Set up feature-flagged dual-runtime scaffold","description":"# Set up feature-flagged dual-runtime scaffold

## Background
To migrate incrementally without breaking the build, we need a period where both tokio and asupersync can coexist. This bead sets up the infrastructure for that coexistence.

## What needs to happen
1. Add feature flag in wa-core/Cargo.toml: asupersync-runtime (default off initially)
2. Create conditional compilation modules:
   - When asupersync-runtime is ON: use asupersync primitives
   - When asupersync-runtime is OFF: use tokio primitives (current behavior)
3. Create abstraction traits that both runtimes can satisfy
4. Ensure CI builds both configurations

## Design
```rust
// src/runtime_compat.rs
#[cfg(feature = "asupersync-runtime")]
pub use asupersync::sync::Mutex;
#[cfg(not(feature = "asupersync-runtime"))]
pub use tokio::sync::Mutex;
// ... etc for all primitives
```

## Important: This is a TEMPORARY scaffold
Once migration is complete, the tokio paths and the compat layer are removed. The feature flag exists only to enable incremental migration — not as a permanent abstraction.

## Acceptance criteria
- Feature flag defined and documented
- Compat module covers: Mutex, RwLock, Semaphore, mpsc, watch, sleep, timeout, spawn
- Both `cargo build` and `cargo build --features asupersync-runtime` succeed
- CI configuration updated to test both

## Feature flag design note
Use `cfg(feature = "asupersync-runtime")` as the primary toggle rather than separate `cfg(feature = "tokio")` / `cfg(feature = "asupersync")` flags. Rationale: tokio is the default (always-on unless asupersync-runtime replaces it), so a single flag with `cfg(not(...))` fallback is simpler and avoids the risk of both features being enabled simultaneously. If dual-enable must be guarded, add a `compile_error!` in lib.rs:
```rust
#[cfg(all(feature = "tokio-runtime", feature = "asupersync-runtime"))]
compile_error!("Cannot enable both tokio-runtime and asupersync-runtime simultaneously");
```

## Property-based testing
- **Proptest for feature flag combinations**: Use proptest to generate arbitrary sequences of runtime operations (spawn, sleep, lock, channel send/recv) and verify that behavior is identical under both `cfg(feature = "asupersync-runtime")` and default (tokio) configurations. This catches any semantic divergence between the two runtime paths during the migration period.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-02-10T03:48:09.153248Z","created_by":"jemanuel","updated_at":"2026-03-29T02:05:50.638337Z","closed_at":"2026-03-29T01:38:37.398066Z","close_reason":"Implemented scaffold already present; committed runtime-matrix CI now enforces both tokio-compat and asupersync-runtime paths","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"wa-1j0ye","depends_on_id":"wa-hj458","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-02-10T03:48:17.492250Z","created_by":"jemanuel","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":2592,"issue_id":"wa-1j0ye","author":"TopazOsprey","text":"Verification split: the committed code already contains a substantial dual-runtime scaffold in `crates/frankenterm-core/src/runtime_compat.rs` (runtime builder/runtime wrappers, mpsc/watch/broadcast/oneshot/notify/task/time/process/io/net/signal surfaces, plus extensive cfg-gated tests). However, the acceptance criterion requiring CI coverage for both runtime modes is not yet satisfied in committed history: the explicit `runtime-matrix` job currently appears only in the uncommitted diff to `.github/workflows/ci.yml`, not in `HEAD`. I am therefore treating this bead as “mostly implemented, not yet safely closable” and staying off the active CI edit surface rather than claiming completion prematurely.","created_at":"2026-03-28T14:51:53Z"},{"id":2598,"issue_id":"wa-1j0ye","author":"TopazOsprey","text":"Status correction: the dual-runtime scaffold is already present in , and the CI coverage gap was closed in committed history by  ( now contains a  job at l